{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"A great way to start, I think, with my view of simplicity"},{"time":4000,"text":"is to take a look at TED. Here you are, understanding why we're here,"},{"time":11000,"text":"what's going on with no difficulty at all."},{"time":16000,"text":"The best A.I. in the planet would find it complex and confusing,"},{"time":20000,"text":"and my little dog Watson would find it simple and understandable"},{"time":25000,"text":"but would miss the point."},{"time":27000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":30000,"text":"He would have a great time."},{"time":33000,"text":"And of course, if you're a speaker here, like Hans Rosling,"},{"time":38000,"text":"a speaker finds this complex, tricky. But in Hans Rosling's case,"},{"time":43000,"text":"he had a secret weapon yesterday,"},{"time":45000,"text":"literally, in his sword swallowing act."},{"time":49000,"text":"And I must say, I thought of quite a few objects"},{"time":51000,"text":"that I might try to swallow today and finally gave up on,"},{"time":56000,"text":"but he just did it and that was a wonderful thing."}]},{"cues":[{"time":60000,"text":"So Puck meant not only are we fools in the pejorative sense,"},{"time":65000,"text":"but that we're easily fooled. In fact, what Shakespeare"},{"time":69000,"text":"was pointing out is we go to the theater in order to be fooled,"},{"time":72000,"text":"so we're actually looking forward to it."},{"time":76000,"text":"We go to magic shows in order to be fooled."},{"time":78000,"text":"And this makes many things fun, but it makes it difficult to actually"},{"time":86000,"text":"get any kind of picture on the world we live in or on ourselves."}]},{"cues":[{"time":90000,"text":"And our friend, Betty Edwards,"},{"time":92000,"text":"the \"Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain\" lady, shows these two tables"},{"time":95000,"text":"to her drawing class and says,"},{"time":100000,"text":"\"The problem you have with learning to draw"},{"time":104000,"text":"is not that you can't move your hand,"},{"time":106000,"text":"but that the way your brain perceives images is faulty."},{"time":112000,"text":"It's trying to perceive images into objects"},{"time":114000,"text":"rather than seeing what's there.\""},{"time":116000,"text":"And to prove it, she says, \"The exact size and shape of these tabletops"},{"time":121000,"text":"is the same, and I'm going to prove it to you.\""},{"time":124000,"text":"She does this with cardboard, but since I have"},{"time":127000,"text":"an expensive computer here"},{"time":130000,"text":"I'll just rotate this little guy around and ..."},{"time":136000,"text":"Now having seen that -- and I've seen it hundreds of times,"},{"time":139000,"text":"because I use this in every talk I give -- I still can't see"},{"time":143000,"text":"that they're the same size and shape, and I doubt that you can either."}]},{"cues":[{"time":148000,"text":"So what do artists do? Well, what artists do is to measure."},{"time":153000,"text":"They measure very, very carefully."},{"time":155000,"text":"And if you measure very, very carefully with a stiff arm and a straight edge,"},{"time":159000,"text":"you'll see that those two shapes are"},{"time":161000,"text":"exactly the same size."},{"time":164000,"text":"And the Talmud saw this a long time ago, saying,"},{"time":169000,"text":"\"We see things not as they are, but as we are.\""},{"time":172000,"text":"I certainly would like to know what happened to the person"},{"time":174000,"text":"who had that insight back then,"},{"time":177000,"text":"if they actually followed it to its ultimate conclusion."}]},{"cues":[{"time":183000,"text":"So if the world is not as it seems and we see things as we are,"},{"time":185000,"text":"then what we call reality is a kind of hallucination"},{"time":191000,"text":"happening inside here. It's a waking dream,"},{"time":194000,"text":"and understanding that that is what we actually exist in"},{"time":199000,"text":"is one of the biggest epistemological barriers in human history."},{"time":204000,"text":"And what that means: \"simple and understandable\""},{"time":206000,"text":"might not be actually simple or understandable,"},{"time":209000,"text":"and things we think are \"complex\" might be made simple and understandable."},{"time":215000,"text":"Somehow we have to understand ourselves to get around our flaws."},{"time":219000,"text":"We can think of ourselves as kind of a noisy channel."},{"time":221000,"text":"The way I think of it is, we can't learn to see"},{"time":226000,"text":"until we admit we're blind."},{"time":228000,"text":"Once you start down at this very humble level,"},{"time":232000,"text":"then you can start finding ways to see things."},{"time":235000,"text":"And what's happened, over the last 400 years in particular,"},{"time":240000,"text":"is that human beings have invented \"brainlets\" --"},{"time":243000,"text":"little additional parts for our brain --"},{"time":247000,"text":"made out of powerful ideas that help us"},{"time":249000,"text":"see the world in different ways."},{"time":251000,"text":"And these are in the form of sensory apparatus --"},{"time":254000,"text":"telescopes, microscopes -- reasoning apparatus --"},{"time":259000,"text":"various ways of thinking -- and, most importantly,"},{"time":263000,"text":"in the ability to change perspective on things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":267000,"text":"I'll talk about that a little bit."},{"time":268000,"text":"It's this change in perspective"},{"time":270000,"text":"on what it is we think we're perceiving"},{"time":273000,"text":"that has helped us make more progress in the last 400 years"},{"time":278000,"text":"than we have in the rest of human history."},{"time":280000,"text":"And yet, it is not taught in any K through 12 curriculum in America that I'm aware of."}]},{"cues":[{"time":293000,"text":"So one of the things that goes from simple to complex"},{"time":295000,"text":"is when we do more. We like more."},{"time":298000,"text":"If we do more in a kind of a stupid way,"},{"time":301000,"text":"the simplicity gets complex"},{"time":304000,"text":"and, in fact, we can keep on doing it for a very long time."},{"time":309000,"text":"But Murray Gell-Mann yesterday talked about emergent properties;"},{"time":312000,"text":"another name for them could be \"architecture\""},{"time":316000,"text":"as a metaphor for taking the same old material"},{"time":320000,"text":"and thinking about non-obvious, non-simple ways of combining it."},{"time":327000,"text":"And in fact, what Murray was talking about yesterday in the fractal beauty of nature --"},{"time":335000,"text":"of having the descriptions"},{"time":337000,"text":"at various levels be rather similar --"},{"time":341000,"text":"all goes down to the idea that the elementary particles"},{"time":346000,"text":"are both sticky and standoffish,"},{"time":349000,"text":"and they're in violent motion."},{"time":353000,"text":"Those three things give rise to all the different levels"},{"time":356000,"text":"of what seem to be complexity in our world."}]},{"cues":[{"time":362000,"text":"But how simple?"},{"time":364000,"text":"So, when I saw Roslings' Gapminder stuff a few years ago,"},{"time":369000,"text":"I just thought it was the greatest thing I'd seen"},{"time":371000,"text":"in conveying complex ideas simply."},{"time":376000,"text":"But then I had a thought of, \"Boy, maybe it's too simple.\""},{"time":379000,"text":"And I put some effort in to try and check"},{"time":384000,"text":"to see how well these simple portrayals of trends over time"},{"time":388000,"text":"actually matched up with some ideas and investigations from the side,"},{"time":393000,"text":"and I found that they matched up very well."},{"time":395000,"text":"So the Roslings have been able to do simplicity"},{"time":400000,"text":"without removing what's important about the data."}]},{"cues":[{"time":404000,"text":"Whereas the film yesterday that we saw"},{"time":408000,"text":"of the simulation of the inside of a cell,"},{"time":410000,"text":"as a former molecular biologist, I didn't like that at all."},{"time":416000,"text":"Not because it wasn't beautiful or anything,"},{"time":418000,"text":"but because it misses the thing that most students fail to understand"},{"time":423000,"text":"about molecular biology, and that is:"},{"time":426000,"text":"why is there any probability at all of two complex shapes"},{"time":431000,"text":"finding each other just the right way"},{"time":433000,"text":"so they combine together and be catalyzed?"},{"time":436000,"text":"And what we saw yesterday was"},{"time":438000,"text":"every reaction was fortuitous;"},{"time":441000,"text":"they just swooped in the air and bound, and something happened."},{"time":445000,"text":"But in fact, those molecules are spinning at the rate of"},{"time":449000,"text":"about a million revolutions per second;"},{"time":452000,"text":"they're agitating back and forth their size every two nanoseconds;"},{"time":458000,"text":"they're completely crowded together, they're jammed,"},{"time":461000,"text":"they're bashing up against each other."},{"time":464000,"text":"And if you don't understand that in your mental model of this stuff,"},{"time":467000,"text":"what happens inside of a cell seems completely mysterious and fortuitous,"},{"time":472000,"text":"and I think that's exactly the wrong image"},{"time":474000,"text":"for when you're trying to teach science."}]},{"cues":[{"time":480000,"text":"So, another thing that we do is to confuse adult sophistication"},{"time":485000,"text":"with the actual understanding of some principle."},{"time":490000,"text":"So a kid who's 14 in high school"},{"time":492000,"text":"gets this version of the Pythagorean theorem,"},{"time":498000,"text":"which is a truly subtle and interesting proof,"},{"time":501000,"text":"but in fact it's not a good way to start learning about mathematics."},{"time":508000,"text":"So a more direct one, one that gives you more of the feeling of math,"},{"time":513000,"text":"is something closer to Pythagoras' own proof, which goes like this:"},{"time":517000,"text":"so here we have this triangle, and if we surround that C square with"},{"time":523000,"text":"three more triangles and we copy that,"},{"time":526000,"text":"notice that we can move those triangles down like this."},{"time":531000,"text":"And that leaves two open areas that are kind of suspicious ..."},{"time":534000,"text":"and bingo. That is all you have to do."},{"time":541000,"text":"And this kind of proof is the kind of proof"},{"time":543000,"text":"that you need to learn when you're learning mathematics"},{"time":546000,"text":"in order to get an idea of what it means"},{"time":549000,"text":"before you look into the, literally, 1,200 or 1,500 proofs"},{"time":553000,"text":"of Pythagoras' theorem that have been discovered."}]},{"cues":[{"time":559000,"text":"Now let's go to young children."},{"time":562000,"text":"This is a very unusual teacher"},{"time":564000,"text":"who was a kindergarten and first-grade teacher,"},{"time":568000,"text":"but was a natural mathematician."},{"time":570000,"text":"So she was like that jazz musician friend you have who never studied music"},{"time":575000,"text":"but is a terrific musician;"},{"time":577000,"text":"she just had a feeling for math."},{"time":579000,"text":"And here are her six-year-olds,"},{"time":582000,"text":"and she's got them making shapes out of a shape."},{"time":587000,"text":"So they pick a shape they like -- like a diamond, or a square,"},{"time":589000,"text":"or a triangle, or a trapezoid -- and then they try and make"},{"time":592000,"text":"the next larger shape of that same shape, and the next larger shape."},{"time":596000,"text":"You can see the trapezoids are a little challenging there."}]},{"cues":[{"time":600000,"text":"And what this teacher did on every project"},{"time":603000,"text":"was to have the children act like first it was a creative arts project,"},{"time":608000,"text":"and then something like science."},{"time":610000,"text":"So they had created these artifacts."},{"time":612000,"text":"Now she had them look at them and do this ... laborious,"},{"time":616000,"text":"which I thought for a long time, until she explained to me was"},{"time":620000,"text":"to slow them down so they'll think."},{"time":623000,"text":"So they're cutting out the little pieces of cardboard here"},{"time":626000,"text":"and pasting them up."}]},{"cues":[{"time":628000,"text":"But the whole point of this thing is"},{"time":632000,"text":"for them to look at this chart and fill it out."},{"time":635000,"text":"\"What have you noticed about what you did?\""},{"time":639000,"text":"And so six-year-old Lauren there noticed that the first one took one,"},{"time":643000,"text":"and the second one took three more"},{"time":648000,"text":"and the total was four on that one,"},{"time":650000,"text":"the third one took five more and the total was nine on that one,"},{"time":654000,"text":"and then the next one."},{"time":655000,"text":"She saw right away that the additional tiles that you had to add"},{"time":660000,"text":"around the edges was always going to grow by two,"},{"time":664000,"text":"so she was very confident about how she made those numbers there."},{"time":667000,"text":"And she could see that these were the square numbers up until about six,"},{"time":672000,"text":"where she wasn't sure what six times six was"},{"time":675000,"text":"and what seven times seven was,"},{"time":677000,"text":"but then she was confident again."},{"time":680000,"text":"So that's what Lauren did."}]},{"cues":[{"time":682000,"text":"And then the teacher, Gillian Ishijima, had the kids"},{"time":686000,"text":"bring all of their projects up to the front of the room and put them on the floor,"},{"time":689000,"text":"and everybody went batshit: \"Holy shit! They're the same!\""},{"time":697000,"text":"No matter what the shapes were, the growth law is the same."},{"time":701000,"text":"And the mathematicians and scientists in the crowd"},{"time":704000,"text":"will recognize these two progressions"},{"time":706000,"text":"as a first-order discrete differential equation"},{"time":709000,"text":"and a second-order discrete differential equation,"},{"time":714000,"text":"derived by six-year-olds."},{"time":718000,"text":"Well, that's pretty amazing."},{"time":719000,"text":"That isn't what we usually try to teach six-year-olds."}]},{"cues":[{"time":722000,"text":"So, let's take a look now at how we might use the computer for some of this."},{"time":729000,"text":"And so the first idea here is"},{"time":733000,"text":"just to show you the kind of things that children do."},{"time":737000,"text":"I'm using the software that we're putting on the $100 laptop."},{"time":742000,"text":"So I'd like to draw a little car here --"},{"time":748000,"text":"I'll just do this very quickly -- and put a big tire on him."},{"time":761000,"text":"And I get a little object here and I can look inside this object,"},{"time":765000,"text":"I'll call it a car. And here's a little behavior: car forward."},{"time":770000,"text":"Each time I click it, car turn."},{"time":773000,"text":"If I want to make a little script to do this over and over again,"},{"time":775000,"text":"I just drag these guys out and set them going."},{"time":782000,"text":"And I can try steering the car here by ..."},{"time":785000,"text":"See the car turn by five here?"},{"time":787000,"text":"So what if I click this down to zero?"},{"time":790000,"text":"It goes straight. That's a big revelation for nine-year-olds."},{"time":795000,"text":"Make it go in the other direction."},{"time":797000,"text":"But of course, that's a little bit like kissing your sister"},{"time":799000,"text":"as far as driving a car,"},{"time":802000,"text":"so the kids want to do a steering wheel;"},{"time":805000,"text":"so they draw a steering wheel."},{"time":808000,"text":"And we'll call this a wheel."},{"time":813000,"text":"See this wheel's heading here?"},{"time":817000,"text":"If I turn this wheel, you can see that number over there going minus and positive."},{"time":822000,"text":"That's kind of an invitation to pick up this name of"},{"time":824000,"text":"those numbers coming out there"},{"time":827000,"text":"and to just drop it into the script here,"},{"time":829000,"text":"and now I can steer the car with the steering wheel."}]},{"cues":[{"time":834000,"text":"And it's interesting."},{"time":836000,"text":"You know how much trouble the children have with variables,"},{"time":839000,"text":"but by learning it this way, in a situated fashion,"},{"time":841000,"text":"they never forget from this single trial"},{"time":844000,"text":"what a variable is and how to use it."},{"time":847000,"text":"And we can reflect here the way Gillian Ishijima did."},{"time":849000,"text":"So if you look at the little script here,"},{"time":851000,"text":"the speed is always going to be 30."},{"time":853000,"text":"We're going to move the car according to that over and over again."},{"time":858000,"text":"And I'm dropping a little dot for each one of these things;"},{"time":862000,"text":"they're evenly spaced because they're 30 apart."},{"time":865000,"text":"And what if I do this progression that the six-year-olds did"},{"time":868000,"text":"of saying, \"OK, I'm going to increase the speed by two each time,"},{"time":873000,"text":"and then I'm going to increase the distance by the speed each time?"},{"time":876000,"text":"What do I get there?\""},{"time":880000,"text":"We get a visual pattern of what these nine-year-olds called acceleration."}]},{"cues":[{"time":887000,"text":"So how do the children do science?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":890000,"text":"(Video) Teacher: [Choose] objects that you think will fall to the Earth at the same time."}]},{"cues":[{"time":893000,"text":"Student 1: Ooh, this is nice."}]},{"cues":[{"time":900000,"text":"Teacher: Do not pay any attention"},{"time":902000,"text":"to what anybody else is doing."},{"time":917000,"text":"Who's got the apple?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":919000,"text":"Alan Kay: They've got little stopwatches."},{"time":926000,"text":"Student 2: What did you get? What did you get?"},{"time":928000,"text":"AK: Stopwatches aren't accurate enough."}]},{"cues":[{"time":931000,"text":"Student 3: 0.99 seconds."}]},{"cues":[{"time":934000,"text":"Teacher: So put \"sponge ball\" ..."}]},{"cues":[{"time":938000,"text":"Student 4l: [I decided to] do the shot put and the sponge ball"},{"time":941000,"text":"because they're two totally different weights,"},{"time":944000,"text":"and if you drop them at the same time,"},{"time":946000,"text":"maybe they'll drop at the same speed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":948000,"text":"Teacher: Drop. Class: Whoa!"}]},{"cues":[{"time":952000,"text":"AK: So obviously, Aristotle never asked a child"},{"time":955000,"text":"about this particular point"},{"time":958000,"text":"because, of course, he didn't bother doing the experiment,"},{"time":960000,"text":"and neither did St. Thomas Aquinas."},{"time":962000,"text":"And it was not until Galileo actually did it"},{"time":964000,"text":"that an adult thought like a child,"},{"time":967000,"text":"only 400 years ago."},{"time":970000,"text":"We get one child like that about every classroom of 30 kids"},{"time":974000,"text":"who will actually cut straight to the chase."}]},{"cues":[{"time":977000,"text":"Now, what if we want to look at this more closely?"},{"time":980000,"text":"We can take a movie of what's going on,"},{"time":983000,"text":"but even if we single stepped this movie,"},{"time":985000,"text":"it's tricky to see what's going on."},{"time":987000,"text":"And so what we can do is we can lay out the frames side by side"},{"time":990000,"text":"or stack them up."},{"time":992000,"text":"So when the children see this, they say, \"Ah! Acceleration,\""},{"time":997000,"text":"remembering back four months when they did their cars sideways,"},{"time":1000000,"text":"and they start measuring to find out what kind of acceleration it is."},{"time":1006000,"text":"So what I'm doing is measuring from the bottom of one image"},{"time":1012000,"text":"to the bottom of the next image, about a fifth of a second later,"},{"time":1017000,"text":"like that. And they're getting faster and faster each time,"},{"time":1019000,"text":"and if I stack these guys up, then we see the differences; the increase"},{"time":1029000,"text":"in the speed is constant."},{"time":1032000,"text":"And they say, \"Oh, yeah. Constant acceleration."},{"time":1034000,"text":"We've done that already.\""},{"time":1036000,"text":"And how shall we look and verify that we actually have it?"},{"time":1044000,"text":"So you can't tell much from just making the ball drop there,"},{"time":1049000,"text":"but if we drop the ball and run the movie at the same time,"},{"time":1055000,"text":"we can see that we have come up with an accurate physical model."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1062000,"text":"Galileo, by the way, did this very cleverly"},{"time":1066000,"text":"by running a ball backwards down the strings of his lute."},{"time":1069000,"text":"I pulled out those apples to remind myself to tell you that"},{"time":1074000,"text":"this is actually probably a Newton and the apple type story,"},{"time":1079000,"text":"but it's a great story."},{"time":1081000,"text":"And I thought I would do just one thing"},{"time":1083000,"text":"on the $100 laptop here just to prove that this stuff works here."},{"time":1093000,"text":"So once you have gravity, here's this --"},{"time":1096000,"text":"increase the speed by something,"},{"time":1098000,"text":"increase the ship's speed."},{"time":1101000,"text":"If I start the little game here that the kids have done,"},{"time":1104000,"text":"it'll crash the space ship."},{"time":1106000,"text":"But if I oppose gravity, here we go ... Oops!"},{"time":1110000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":1112000,"text":"One more."},{"time":1116000,"text":"Yeah, there we go. Yeah, OK?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1121000,"text":"I guess the best way to end this is with two quotes:"},{"time":1128000,"text":"Marshall McLuhan said,"},{"time":1130000,"text":"\"Children are the messages that we send to the future,\""},{"time":1134000,"text":"but in fact, if you think of it,"},{"time":1136000,"text":"children are the future we send to the future."},{"time":1138000,"text":"Forget about messages;"},{"time":1141000,"text":"children are the future,"},{"time":1144000,"text":"and children in the first and second world"},{"time":1146000,"text":"and, most especially, in the third world"},{"time":1149000,"text":"need mentors."},{"time":1151000,"text":"And this summer, we're going to build five million of these $100 laptops,"},{"time":1156000,"text":"and maybe 50 million next year."},{"time":1158000,"text":"But we couldn't create 1,000 new teachers this summer to save our life."},{"time":1165000,"text":"That means that we, once again, have a thing where we can put technology out,"},{"time":1171000,"text":"but the mentoring that is required to go"},{"time":1174000,"text":"from a simple new iChat instant messaging system"},{"time":1179000,"text":"to something with depth is missing."},{"time":1181000,"text":"I believe this has to be done with a new kind of user interface,"},{"time":1184000,"text":"and this new kind of user interface could be done"},{"time":1188000,"text":"with an expenditure of about 100 million dollars."},{"time":1193000,"text":"It sounds like a lot, but it is literally 18 minutes of what we're spending in Iraq --"},{"time":1200000,"text":"we're spending 8 billion dollars a month; 18 minutes is 100 million dollars --"},{"time":1205000,"text":"so this is actually cheap."},{"time":1207000,"text":"And Einstein said,"},{"time":1211000,"text":"\"Things should be as simple as possible, but not simpler.\""},{"time":1214000,"text":"Thank you."}]}]}